---
import LessonLayout from '../../layouts/LessonLayout.astro';
---
<LessonLayout
  title="Hello, Reachy!"
  track="little-explorers"
  week={4}
  phase="Phase 2: Meet Reachy"
  duration="30 min"
  emoji="👋"
  objective="Meet our robot friend and say hello for the first time"
>
  <section class="lesson-section mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-explorer-700 mb-3">🎯 Learning Objective</h2>
    <p class="bg-explorer-50 border-l-4 border-explorer-400 p-4 rounded-r-xl text-gray-700">
      Your child will see Reachy Mini for the first time (in simulator mode), interact with it gently, and begin to feel comfortable around robots.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="lesson-section mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-3">🛠️ Materials</h2>
    <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
      <li class="flex items-center gap-2">✅ Computer or tablet with Python installed</li>
      <li class="flex items-center gap-2">✅ Reachy Mini SDK: <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded">pip install reachy-mini</code></li>
      <li class="flex items-center gap-2">✅ The "instruction cards" from Week 3</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="lesson-section mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-3">📋 Activity Steps</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <div class="flex gap-4 items-start">
        <span class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-explorer-500 text-white font-bold flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">1</span>
        <div><h3 class="font-bold">Introduce Reachy (5 min)</h3><p class="text-gray-600">Show your child a picture or video of Reachy Mini. "This is Reachy! It's a robot that we can give instructions to — just like our game last week." Point out the arms, head, and eyes (cameras).</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="flex gap-4 items-start">
        <span class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-explorer-500 text-white font-bold flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">2</span>
        <div><h3 class="font-bold">Run the Hello Script (15 min)</h3><p class="text-gray-600">Open a terminal together. Run the code below. Watch the output! Ask your child to "read" what Reachy says.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="flex gap-4 items-start">
        <span class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-explorer-500 text-white font-bold flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">3</span>
        <div><h3 class="font-bold">Decorate Reachy's Name Tag (5 min)</h3><p class="text-gray-600">Make a name tag for Reachy on paper. Write "REACHY" and decorate it together.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="flex gap-4 items-start">
        <span class="w-8 h-8 rounded-full bg-explorer-500 text-white font-bold flex items-center justify-center flex-shrink-0">4</span>
        <div><h3 class="font-bold">Wrap Up (5 min)</h3><p class="text-gray-600">Ask: "What do you want to teach Reachy to do?" Write or draw their answer to refer to later.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="lesson-section mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-3">💻 Code Snippet</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-600 mb-3">Save this as <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded">hello_reachy.py</code> and run with <code class="bg-gray-100 px-1 rounded">python hello_reachy.py</code></p>
    <pre is:raw class="bg-gray-900 text-green-300 rounded-xl p-5 overflow-x-auto text-sm leading-relaxed"><code># hello_reachy.py — Week 4: Little Explorers
# Works in simulator mode — no hardware needed!

import time

class ReachyMock:
    """A pretend Reachy for when the real one isn't connected."""
    def __init__(self):
        print("🤖 Reachy is waking up... (simulator mode)")
        time.sleep(1)
        print("🤖 Hello! I am Reachy Mini!")
        print("🤖 I am ready to be your robot friend.")

    def say(self, message):
        print(f"🤖 Reachy says: '{message}'")
        time.sleep(0.5)

# Try to connect to real Reachy; fall back to simulator
try:
    from reachy_mini import ReachyMini
    robot = ReachyMini()
    print("✅ Connected to real Reachy!")
except Exception:
    robot = ReachyMock()
    print("🎮 Using simulator mode")

# Say hello!
robot.say("Hello, little explorer!")
robot.say("I am so happy to meet you!")
robot.say("What shall we do today?")</code></pre>
  </section>

  <section class="lesson-section mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-3">💬 Reflection Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-3">
      <div class="bg-yellow-50 border border-yellow-200 rounded-xl p-4"><p class="font-semibold text-yellow-800">🌟 "What did you like best about meeting Reachy?"</p></div>
      <div class="bg-yellow-50 border border-yellow-200 rounded-xl p-4"><p class="font-semibold text-yellow-800">🌟 "Does Reachy have feelings? Why do you think that?"</p></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="lesson-section mb-8">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-800 mb-3">👪 Parent Tips</h2>
    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-xl p-5 text-gray-700">
      <p>💡 Let your child press Enter to run the code — that moment of agency is powerful. Say "YOU just gave Reachy instructions!"</p>
      <p class="mt-2">💡 The mock/simulator pattern means this works with no hardware. All future lessons use the same try/except approach.</p>
    </div>
  </section>
</LessonLayout>
